    "709689": {
      "title": "Fluorochrome-labelled lectins reveal secreted glycoconjugates of schistosome larvae",
      "abstract": "Schistosomiasis infection results from contact with waters containing free- swimming schistosome larvae (cercariae) emerging from infected snails. Penetra- tion of the skin by a cercaria involves complex morphological and biochemical changes associated with the transition from water to the host environment. Special interest in the penetration stage is motivated by the prospect of interfer- ing with the process as a means of pro- tection against infection. After penetrating the host, the cer- carla transforms to a schistosomulum which negotiates the epidermis, base- ment membranes and connective tissues of the host skin. Penetration appears to depend on the secretion of enzymes from the larval penetration glands, such as proteinases, which degrade the major connective tissue and basement mem- brane constituents, fibronection and laminin l . Penetration is dependent on the transformation from cercaria to schisto- somulum, which involves shedding the cercarial tail and the glycocalyx of the cer- carial body, and is accompanied by release of acetabular gland contents. These events are usually regarded as part of the pene- tration process, but they can be con- sidered as separate phenomena in a chain of events initiated by recogn~on of essen- tial fatty acids of the skinZ3 and followed by attachment to the skin surface. To supplement the picture of these events preceding actual penetration, an in vitro model was designed for studying recognition and attachment. Histochem- ical staining methods show that the cercarial penetration glands contain"
    },
    "2537272": {
      "title": "Isolation of an SBA lectin-reactive glycoprotein (GP50) and its identification in Schistosoma mansoni larval and adult worm secretions",
      "abstract": "A major 50-kDa soybean agglutinin (SBA)-reactive component present in extracts of Schistosoma mansoni eggs was isolated by SBA lectin affinity chromatography. In polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis (PAGE), the SBA-reactive component was seen as a 100-kDa polypeptide band that after reduction and alcylation was substituted by a 50-kDa component. This suggests that it occurs in native form as a dimer. Monoclonal antibodies produced against gpS0 reacted with miracidial and cercarial secretions and with adult worm components including tegumental structures suggestive of a secretory function. Fluorochrome-labeled lectins can be used to visualize secretions produced by 2 schistosome larval stages, cercariae and miracidia. Secretions are involved in various phenomena at the host- parasite interface, not only in attachment and"
    }
